00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:56.110
in the animation, the
concept of mirror neurons.

00:20:56.110 --> 00:20:58.510
Have you heard of those?

00:20:58.510 --> 00:20:59.230
OK.

00:20:59.230 --> 00:21:01.650
So do you want to tell us?

00:21:01.650 --> 00:21:02.150
OK.

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:04.295
AUDIENCE: There's some
controversy about what

00:21:04.295 --> 00:21:05.507
they actually mean, but--

00:21:05.507 --> 00:21:06.340
MICHAEL NAGLER: Yes.

00:21:06.340 --> 00:21:08.680
Well, there's controversy
about everything,

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:14.450
but one aspect of it
is that, for example,

00:21:14.450 --> 00:21:20.140
if somebody is writing,
the motor neurons that

00:21:20.140 --> 00:21:23.560
would make me write are
fired just by observing that,

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:25.720
even though I'm
not writing myself.

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:28.240
At the last minute,
there's another set

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:33.280
of neurons, which intersects
that process and says,

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:37.780
you're not Ziggy, so you
don't have to go like this.

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:39.280
Now, that's, of
course, critically

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:42.490
important for nonviolence
because in nonviolence,

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:46.350
the power comes from being able
to, as we call it nowadays,

00:21:46.350 --> 00:21:47.890
flip the switch.

00:21:47.890 --> 00:21:50.650
Somebody comes at
you with a threat.

00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:52.750
The script is,
you're supposed to be

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:55.970
going into fear and compliance.

00:21:55.970 --> 00:22:01.960
But as Ken Butigan showed
you in the trailer,

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:06.760
you say instead, I refuse to
go along with your coercion,

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:08.200
but I accept--

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:10.060
I'm open to you
as a human being.

00:22:10.060 --> 00:22:11.960
And you flip that script.

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:15.730
So when I completely
change my mental state,

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:18.550
your mirror neurons
resonate with that.

00:22:18.550 --> 00:22:20.500
It doesn't, 100% of the
time, mean that you're

00:22:20.500 --> 00:22:21.830
going to change your behavior.

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:27.010
But it does mean that
more often and more safely

00:22:27.010 --> 00:22:29.680
than if you try to
get a person to change

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:33.010
through threat of violence.

00:22:33.010 --> 00:22:39.460
So any-- this is my whole career
I'm condensing into one hour,

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:42.400
so I know I'm
going kind of fast.

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:45.700
If you have any questions, let
me pause here briefly to see.

00:22:45.700 --> 00:22:47.800
Yeah.

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:50.884
AUDIENCE: I'm curious about
that last point about--

00:22:50.884 --> 00:22:52.300
you're saying
flipping the switch,

00:22:52.300 --> 00:22:53.350
changing the dynamics
of the situation.

00:22:53.350 --> 00:22:54.370
MICHAEL NAGLER:
Flipping the script.

00:22:54.370 --> 00:22:55.911
AUDIENCE: Flipping
the script, sorry.

00:22:55.911 --> 00:22:57.280
MICHAEL NAGLER: Yeah.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:22:59.400
AUDIENCE: You know,
in psychology, there's

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:01.655
also discussion about
sociopaths, people

00:23:01.655 --> 00:23:05.650
who would perceive the
emotions of others,

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:08.380
but don't experience that
kind of empathic response.

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:11.020
How do you account for that
or how do you respond to that?

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:11.936
MICHAEL NAGLER: Right.

00:23:11.936 --> 00:23:14.410
What do you do with
a real sociopath?

00:23:14.410 --> 00:23:16.810
Well, that's going
to be hard, and it's

00:23:16.810 --> 00:23:19.000
going to be a lot harder
than with a normally

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.280
empathic person.

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:24.530
But it turns out that even
there, it's not impossible.

00:23:24.530 --> 00:23:26.770
And when we do the
workshop right after this,

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:29.140
we'll show you some
examples of that.

00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:33.190
Because what you're doing is
actually appealing to something

00:23:33.190 --> 00:23:38.110
even deeper than that
sociopathology, which has been

00:23:38.110 --> 00:23:40.450
conditioned into the person.

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:43.180
Something inside of
them which they are not

00:23:43.180 --> 00:23:45.694
even consciously aware of.

00:23:45.694 --> 00:23:47.110
In fact, that's
one of the reasons

00:23:47.110 --> 00:23:50.170
that nonviolence is such
a powerful contributor

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:52.620
to positive social change.

00:23:52.620 --> 00:23:55.630
It elicits things from
people that they're not

00:23:55.630 --> 00:23:57.870
even aware is there.

00:23:57.870 --> 00:24:00.110
I have a very dear
friend whose parents

00:24:00.110 --> 00:24:05.860
were in the
underground in Warsaw

00:24:05.860 --> 00:24:08.230
during the Nazi occupation.

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:10.900
And a Gestapo came
to their apartment

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:14.740
and found these
incriminating papers,

00:24:14.740 --> 00:24:17.450
was about to arrest them.

00:24:17.450 --> 00:24:21.520
Needless to say here,
Jewish in the underground.

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:25.030
But this couple had
a four-year-old boy

00:24:25.030 --> 00:24:28.420
and he was fascinated by
the buttons on the Gestapo

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:30.160
captain's uniform.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:32.215
So to the horror of
the parents, here he

00:24:32.215 --> 00:24:34.270
is playing with these buttons.

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:37.480
The captain looked down and
suddenly, he just completely

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:38.820
changed.

00:24:38.820 --> 00:24:44.160
He said, I have a little boy
at home who is just his age.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:46.590
And he said, I miss
him-- excuse me--

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:48.700
I miss him very much.

00:24:48.700 --> 00:24:53.760
And then he ordered his
men to leave the apartment.

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:56.040
And then the couple
survived the war

00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:59.145
and actually became the parents
of a very good friend of mine

00:24:59.145 --> 00:25:01.290
who's in the peace movement.

00:25:01.290 --> 00:25:03.930
So what we do in
nonviolence is we

00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:09.830
learn the techniques to elicit
that change deliberately.

00:25:09.830 --> 00:25:12.671
We will go into that
in the workshop.

00:25:12.671 --> 00:25:13.170
Good.

00:25:13.170 --> 00:25:16.067
Any other comments
before I roll on?

00:25:16.067 --> 00:25:18.150
AUDIENCE: I had a quick
question about the trailer

00:25:18.150 --> 00:25:21.054
that you just showed us
and general questions

00:25:21.054 --> 00:25:22.220
about a reformative justice.

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:23.610
I'm happy to wait if
that's something that's

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:25.026
going to be featured
in your talk,

00:25:25.026 --> 00:25:27.630
but otherwise I'll
go ahead and ask.

00:25:27.630 --> 00:25:30.120
I mean, is reformative justice--

00:25:30.120 --> 00:25:31.620
MICHAEL NAGLER:
Restorative justice?

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:32.400
AUDIENCE: Restorative justice.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:32.790
MICHAEL NAGLER: Yes.

00:25:32.790 --> 00:25:35.248
AUDIENCE: Is that something
that you're going to touch upon

00:25:35.248 --> 00:25:36.719
during the course of the talk?

00:25:36.719 --> 00:25:38.760
MICHAEL NAGLER: Now that
you brought it up, sure.

00:25:38.760 --> 00:25:40.175
Yes, I'd be happy to.

00:25:40.175 --> 00:25:40.800
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:44.790
MICHAEL NAGLER: Restorative
justice is based on the idea

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:49.800
that when there's
been what is otherwise

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:55.200
called a crime, what's
actually at issue is harm.

00:25:55.200 --> 00:25:59.610
Not a crime in law, but
harm to human relationships.

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:01.980
And you want to restore
that relationship.

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:06.610
You don't do that by locking the
person who offended you away.

00:26:06.610 --> 00:26:09.930
You make it impossible to
restore that relationship.

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:14.670
So you bring them back in
and set up a safe zone where

00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:16.980
they can say two things.

00:26:16.980 --> 00:26:18.990
They can say here's
why I did it.

00:26:18.990 --> 00:26:23.130
And sometimes, these people
have horrendous stories of abuse

00:26:23.130 --> 00:26:24.870
in their background,
which changes

00:26:24.870 --> 00:26:26.760
the atmosphere a little bit.

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:29.340
And then they take
responsibility

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:31.470
and say, what can I do?

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:33.780
A lot of this
restorative behavior

00:26:33.780 --> 00:26:38.280
has been practiced in indigenous
cultures for a long time.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:41.390
And in one case that I
find really dramatic,

00:26:41.390 --> 00:26:47.190
there is a large community
in sub-Saharan Africa called

00:26:47.190 --> 00:26:48.300
the Bemba.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:51.820
And when somebody offends
in that community,

00:26:51.820 --> 00:26:54.630
they are made to sit in a
circle with the whole village

00:26:54.630 --> 00:26:56.310
around them.

00:26:56.310 --> 00:27:00.090
And they go around that circle
and everyone in the village

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:03.617
is required to say something
good about that person.

00:27:03.617 --> 00:27:05.700
And when they get about
halfway around the circle,

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:09.270
usually the person, the guy--
it's almost always a guy--

00:27:09.270 --> 00:27:13.150
breaks down and has a
complete change of heart,

00:27:13.150 --> 00:27:16.500
and then they work
out a restitution

00:27:16.500 --> 00:27:21.700
for the harm that's been done,
and they rebuild the community.

00:27:21.700 --> 00:27:25.020
So we were in a meeting in
the Santa Rosa school system

00:27:25.020 --> 00:27:28.920
not long ago where they had
introduced restorative justice

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:35.520
in the schools, and the
expulsion and suspension rate

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:41.320
went from 60 cases to
two in the first year.

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:44.500
It was on its way to being zero.

00:27:44.500 --> 00:27:46.620
There was one
educator down south,

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:49.446
San Diego, who was
completely against this--

00:27:49.446 --> 00:27:50.820
it would never
work in my school.

00:27:50.820 --> 00:27:52.590
It's way too tough.

00:27:52.590 --> 00:27:54.810
And he's now one of
the biggest supporters.

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:56.910
And I asked him, what
was the big change?

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:00.480
And he said, every time
I did the normal system,

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:02.740
I lost a relationship.

00:28:02.740 --> 00:28:07.050
That's because that's what the
"normal," unquote, system does.

00:28:07.050 --> 00:28:12.160
Every time I do restorative
justice, I gain a relationship.

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:16.290
So we have a long range
program at Metta Center

00:28:16.290 --> 00:28:20.010
to try to get restorative
justice into the schools.

00:28:20.010 --> 00:28:22.770
And then when it's really
established in the schools,

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:24.222
get it into the prisons.

00:28:24.222 --> 00:28:25.680
And when it's
established in there,

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:26.721
we could get it anywhere.

00:28:26.721 --> 00:28:30.880
We could get rid of
the whole war system.

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:32.860
So as Martin Luther
King would say,

00:28:32.860 --> 00:28:38.500
I may not get there with
you, but it is a very good

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:42.620
trajectory to work on.

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:43.140
OK.

00:28:43.140 --> 00:28:47.240
So let me now take us
a little bit deeper

00:28:47.240 --> 00:28:48.690
into what nonviolence is.

00:28:48.690 --> 00:28:51.240
And these have been
very good questions,

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:54.830
so please keep them coming.

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:58.490
So this is just our
introductory slide,

00:28:58.490 --> 00:29:01.040
helping people practice
nonviolence more

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:03.200
safely and more effectively.

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:08.430
I think you know that gentleman
with the spinning wheel.

00:29:08.430 --> 00:29:13.190
So I wanted to illustrate what
the Old Story is doing to us.

00:29:13.190 --> 00:29:15.170
This is a billboard
that was not far

00:29:15.170 --> 00:29:17.750
from our office in Petaluma.

00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:21.200
And I wanted to emphasize
the motto in red

00:29:21.200 --> 00:29:25.610
at the top of this billboard,
"Our Pain is Your Gain."

00:29:25.610 --> 00:29:29.190
In other words, if you can
make us suffer, you win.

00:29:29.190 --> 00:29:33.950
You'll be advancing
yourself by putting us down.

00:29:33.950 --> 00:29:37.340
Now, let me project this
against a model that

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:41.490
was developed by one of the
greatest peace researchers

00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:45.380
that we had in the English
language, Kenneth Boulding.

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:48.230
And towards the end
of his life, Kenneth

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:51.770
wrote a book called "The
Three Faces of Power."

00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:54.650
He said we have three
ways of getting a person

00:29:54.650 --> 00:29:58.060
to do something,
otherwise known as power.

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:03.210
There is threat power, where
essentially you're saying,

00:30:03.210 --> 00:30:06.960
do what I want or I'll do
something you don't want.

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:11.390
There's exchange power, where
essentially you're saying,

00:30:11.390 --> 00:30:12.860
give me something
I want and I'll

00:30:12.860 --> 00:30:15.050
give you something you want.

00:30:15.050 --> 00:30:17.930
And finally, but the
most important and least

00:30:17.930 --> 00:30:21.610
studied, is one called
integrative power,

00:30:21.610 --> 00:30:23.840
where you say, I am
going to be authentic

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:26.750
and we will end up closer.

00:30:26.750 --> 00:30:32.630
Now, exchange power is kind of
in a middle zone between threat

00:30:32.630 --> 00:30:35.180
power, which is
clearly violence,

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:38.720
and integrative power,
which is nonviolence.

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:42.410
And you can run exchange
power in both ways.

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:45.650
Here, we have an example
of exchange power

00:30:45.650 --> 00:30:49.580
being used to create
violence on a subtle level.

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:52.450
While it's selling
you some real estate,

00:30:52.450 --> 00:30:56.060
it is also selling you
on the Old Story idea

00:30:56.060 --> 00:30:57.500
that in order for
you to be happy,

00:30:57.500 --> 00:31:01.400
somebody else probably
has to suffer.

00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:03.860
I promise you the
tour of the Old Story

00:31:03.860 --> 00:31:05.520
is not going to be too long.

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:08.300
We'll get to nonviolence soon.

00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:12.590
But here's another
subtle example of it.

00:31:15.230 --> 00:31:18.230
The reason this
offends me so much--

00:31:18.230 --> 00:31:19.760
may not offend you--

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:24.440
is that inner peace is
a very important concept

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:28.700
and to trivialize it with the
idea of outer purchasing--

00:31:28.700 --> 00:31:30.800
and we've gotten inured to this.

00:31:30.800 --> 00:31:32.660
It goes on and on.

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:35.720
But my PhD was in a subject
called comparative literature,

00:31:35.720 --> 00:31:37.970
so I'm very sensitive
to what people are

00:31:37.970 --> 00:31:40.310
being told under the surface.

00:31:40.310 --> 00:31:43.250
It's subtler and more
powerful than what they're

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:44.870
being told on the surface.

00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:49.270
So on the surface, you're being
told buy a Dell hard drive.

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:52.400
Don't want to mention
brand names here.

00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:54.510
Under the surface,
they're saying--

00:31:54.510 --> 00:31:57.050
as we said, it's showed
in the animation--

00:31:57.050 --> 00:31:59.750
the way to happiness
is through purchases.

00:31:59.750 --> 00:32:02.210
In other words, there is
no happiness within you,

00:32:02.210 --> 00:32:04.800
which is a huge lie.

00:32:04.800 --> 00:32:05.300
OK.

00:32:05.300 --> 00:32:09.650
So this is probably a stark
statement of the New Story.

00:32:09.650 --> 00:32:13.800
When you want real wisdom in
this world, where do you go?

00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:17.210
You go to bumper
stickers, right?

00:32:17.210 --> 00:32:21.590
There was a bumper sticker in
my part of town a while back

00:32:21.590 --> 00:32:25.190
which said, "My wife says
I don't listen to her.

00:32:25.190 --> 00:32:28.350
At least I think
that's what she said."

00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:31.550
And this one says, "We are
not human beings having

00:32:31.550 --> 00:32:34.820
a spiritual experience"-- which
you will hear every other day

00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:36.410
in Marin County--

00:32:36.410 --> 00:32:38.910
"we are spiritual beings
having a human experience."

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:41.585
In other words, we
are fundamentally

00:32:41.585 --> 00:32:45.660
a spirit who have
entered a human context.

00:32:45.660 --> 00:32:47.490
Again, I'm moving
very fast, so please

00:32:47.490 --> 00:32:50.730
feel free to stick your
hand up or jot down

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:52.870
a question for later.

00:32:52.870 --> 00:32:56.550
Now, in the trailer,
you saw an interview

00:32:56.550 --> 00:33:00.350
with a woman named
Erica Chenoweth.

00:33:00.350 --> 00:33:03.390
To back up a second,
back in the '70s,

00:33:03.390 --> 00:33:05.260
there was a book
by a couple called

00:33:05.260 --> 00:33:08.460
Lind, Staughton and
Alice Lind, called

00:33:08.460 --> 00:33:11.190
"Nonviolence in America."

00:33:11.190 --> 00:33:14.340
That's an arresting
title, to be sure.

00:33:14.340 --> 00:33:17.150
And yes, it was a full
book, believe it or not,

00:33:17.150 --> 00:33:20.902
with actual content and a
table of contents and an index

00:33:20.902 --> 00:33:22.110
and all of those good things.

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:24.360
You get a PhD on this stuff.

00:33:24.360 --> 00:33:27.240
And one of the things that
they said in their introduction

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:31.080
to the book is the way
that social science

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:38.430
has ignored this story and let
it disappear is a disgrace.

00:33:38.430 --> 00:33:41.820
So fortunately, in just
the last few years--

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:43.410
just the last few years--

00:33:43.410 --> 00:33:45.180
this has changed.

00:33:45.180 --> 00:33:48.000
And Erica Chenoweth
and Maria Stephan

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.760
have written a very
compelling book called

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:53.310
"Why Civil Resistance Works."

00:33:53.310 --> 00:33:56.580
They're using the word civil
resistance for nonviolence.

00:33:56.580 --> 00:33:59.700
And just to summarize
some of their discoveries,

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:02.490
they explored almost
300 cases of what

00:34:02.490 --> 00:34:05.910
we call insurrectionary
movements, regime

00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:08.850
change through uprisings.

00:34:08.850 --> 00:34:11.130
And if they were
violent, they were

00:34:11.130 --> 00:34:15.389
successful 26% of the time.

00:34:15.389 --> 00:34:20.909
If they were nonviolent,
meaning weapon-free, so forth--

00:34:20.909 --> 00:34:24.900
depending on strikes and
non-cooperation techniques,

00:34:24.900 --> 00:34:26.219
things of that kind--

00:34:26.219 --> 00:34:29.820
they were successful
56% of the time.

00:34:29.820 --> 00:34:33.690
If they were violent,
they took 9 to 10 years

00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:36.570
to run their course,
usually ending up

00:34:36.570 --> 00:34:39.719
in a battle of attrition,
kind of a civil war.

00:34:39.719 --> 00:34:43.949
If they were nonviolent, it
took from two to three years.

00:34:43.949 --> 00:34:47.550
And they were more likely to
lead to democratic conditions

00:34:47.550 --> 00:34:51.630
five years down the road,
even if they, quote, "failed."

00:34:51.630 --> 00:34:55.400
Failed, that is to say,
to overthrow a dictator

00:34:55.400 --> 00:34:57.760
or whatever it was
they were aiming at.

00:34:57.760 --> 00:35:00.600
So you overthrow a
dictator through violence,

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:04.070
you don't get a
free civilization.

00:35:04.070 --> 00:35:08.562
As Gandhi said-- he kept
coming to Gandhi and saying,

00:35:08.562 --> 00:35:10.770
when are you going to stop
with this nonviolent stuff

00:35:10.770 --> 00:35:12.870
and get to the real revolution?

00:35:12.870 --> 00:35:15.630
And he said, violent
revolution will

00:35:15.630 --> 00:35:20.495
lead to violence [INAUDIBLE],,
a violent regime.

00:35:20.495 --> 00:35:24.690
A nonviolent revolution will
lead to a nonviolent regime,

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:27.660
even if it "fails,"
quote, unquote, to do

00:35:27.660 --> 00:35:30.920
what you were trying to do.

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:33.860
I can expand on any
of these points,

00:35:33.860 --> 00:35:36.710
but I think, for now, I'm
just trying to introduce you

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:39.590
to the scope of things.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:43.420
So this gives us an
idea of what nonviolence

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:45.470
looked like in the Old Story.

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:50.060
And we usually, today, call
that strategic nonviolence.

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:53.510
And what it looks like in the
New Story, and that's called

00:35:53.510 --> 00:35:55.790
principled nonviolence.

00:35:55.790 --> 00:35:57.320
So we'll take this one episode.

00:35:57.320 --> 00:35:59.930
This is an uprising in Yemen.

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:03.080
You can see those people
are pretty agitated.

00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:06.950
And they had a
slogan, which was,

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:11.060
"They can't defeat us because
we left our weapons at home."

00:36:11.060 --> 00:36:14.310
Now, that is basically true.

00:36:14.310 --> 00:36:17.330
It turns out that
if you use weapons,

00:36:17.330 --> 00:36:20.570
you're actually
producing violence.

00:36:20.570 --> 00:36:25.430
Something like 70% of
homicides these days

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:28.880
are what's called victim
precipitated homicides.

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:33.180
You pull out a weapon to defend
yourself, you get blown away.

00:36:33.180 --> 00:36:35.780
So I'm not disputing
the truth of that,

00:36:35.780 --> 00:36:38.630
but in strategic
nonviolence, you

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:44.450
look at a person as a rational,
cost benefit calculator

00:36:44.450 --> 00:36:47.990
and try to, more or
less, force that person

00:36:47.990 --> 00:36:52.130
to do what you want by
changing conditions.

00:36:52.130 --> 00:36:54.170
Whereas in principled
nonviolence,

00:36:54.170 --> 00:36:57.554
you might have said, "We
will win them over"--

00:36:57.554 --> 00:36:58.970
instead of "they
can't defeat us."

00:36:58.970 --> 00:37:03.680
"We will win them over because
we left our hatred at home."

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:08.150
And that's why it is difficult
to understand real nonviolence

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:12.380
in the Old Story because
we do not acknowledge

00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:13.905
the power of inner states.

00:37:18.910 --> 00:37:24.000
So here's someone who
acknowledged them.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.490
And this is one of the
most important statements

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:30.470
in the history of nonviolence.

00:37:30.470 --> 00:37:35.900
"I have learnt the one supreme
lesson to conserve my anger,

00:37:35.900 --> 00:37:39.920
and as heat conserved is
transmuted into energy,

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:43.700
our anger controlled can be
transmuted into a power that

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:46.810
can move the world."

00:37:46.810 --> 00:37:48.580
One other little
complaint that I

00:37:48.580 --> 00:37:50.640
have about Richard
Attenborough's film

00:37:50.640 --> 00:37:54.040
is it does not show you
how angry Gandhi was.

00:37:54.040 --> 00:37:56.270
Oh, my gosh, was he angry.

00:37:56.270 --> 00:38:00.730
But he had something to do with
it, and not just let it out,

00:38:00.730 --> 00:38:04.964
which is a huge mistake that's
done with many movements today.

00:38:04.964 --> 00:38:06.880
A lot of people think
that all they need to do

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:09.850
is show others how
angry they are,

00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:11.350
and they will have
made their point.

00:38:11.350 --> 00:38:14.320
Well, given the mirror
neurons, if you show people

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:17.330
how angry they are, they'll
get much more angry at you.

00:38:17.330 --> 00:38:19.630
And where do you go?

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:21.880
So because this
is so important, I

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:24.400
like to dwell on it
just a little bit more.

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:28.570
"Civil disobedience," a part
of one of the nonviolent

00:38:28.570 --> 00:38:31.810
strategies, "is a
sovereign method

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:36.790
of transforming undisciplined,
life-destroying latent energy

00:38:36.790 --> 00:38:40.580
into disciplined,
life-saving energy."

00:38:40.580 --> 00:38:45.070
So again, this capacity to
talk about our inner energies

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:47.770
is made much more
possible when you

00:38:47.770 --> 00:38:50.920
see that we are body,
mind, and spirit and not

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:53.950
just molecules
being knocked around

00:38:53.950 --> 00:38:57.940
by other molecules for
no particular reason.

00:38:57.940 --> 00:39:03.070
And Martin Luther King
enlarged on this when he said

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:04.720
almost exactly the same thing.

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:07.040
"We caused no
outbursts of anger.

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:12.960
We expressed anger under
discipline for maximum effect."

00:39:12.960 --> 00:39:15.200
And this is what Gandhi did.

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:17.630
I mean, my meditation
teacher claims

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:20.300
that Gandhi was one
of the angriest people

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:24.650
in the 20th century, but he
expressed it under discipline.

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:27.140
Meaning, I am not going
to put up with this.

00:39:27.140 --> 00:39:29.630
I'm going to make
this situation change.

00:39:29.630 --> 00:39:33.785
So he's thrown off a
train in 1893, the march

00:39:33.785 --> 00:39:35.600
in Pietermaritzburg.

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:40.790
He is volcanically angry.

00:39:40.790 --> 00:39:42.680
But instead of saying,
they did this to me,

00:39:42.680 --> 00:39:45.290
they can't get away
with it, he said,

00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:47.990
this is man's inhumanity
to man, and we

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:49.820
must do something about it.

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:51.910
And you see that in
the Attenborough film.

00:39:51.910 --> 00:39:54.710
And when you choose
a constructive path,

00:39:54.710 --> 00:39:59.240
the anger is converted
into creative energy.

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:01.730
You don't have to actually
know how it's happening

00:40:01.730 --> 00:40:04.970
and do it, you just make that
right choice that you are not

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:06.800
going to yield to
anger, you're going

00:40:06.800 --> 00:40:08.480
to do something constructive.

00:40:08.480 --> 00:40:12.590
All the power of that anger,
which is considerable--

00:40:12.590 --> 00:40:16.250
playing upon that power,
as somebody recently said,

00:40:16.250 --> 00:40:19.640
which got us the President that
we have now in this country,

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:22.550
no names please.

00:40:22.550 --> 00:40:25.120
So that power is
there in all of us.

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:28.280
And for those of us who
are sensitive to injustice,

00:40:28.280 --> 00:40:30.040
that power can be very--

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:31.850
it can be extreme.

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:36.610
But if we know how to deal
with it, it enlarges us,

00:40:36.610 --> 00:40:40.160
it advances us
spiritually, and it changes

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:41.880
the situation for the better.

00:40:41.880 --> 00:40:44.060
That's nonviolence
in a nutshell.

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:52.940
One of the things that is useful
to know about any conflict

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:56.220
is how far along you
are in that conflict.

00:40:56.220 --> 00:41:02.130
So we've created this kind
of pseudoscientific graph,

00:41:02.130 --> 00:41:06.470
if you will, that plots the
level of dehumanization, which

00:41:06.470 --> 00:41:11.420
is what makes conflicts extreme,
and the amount of violence

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:12.230
it leads to.

00:41:12.230 --> 00:41:17.960
And generally speaking, the
escalation of conflict goes--

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:21.380
it can shoot up very rapidly,
especially in the presence

00:41:21.380 --> 00:41:23.990
of a weapon or so forth.

00:41:23.990 --> 00:41:28.190
Now, what we want to do in
nonviolence is de-escalate,

00:41:28.190 --> 00:41:30.300
go back in the other direction.

00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:32.420
That is simple enough.

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:37.670
But it's helpful, we find,
to segment that curve

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:41.540
into three sections, and know
which section your conflict

00:41:41.540 --> 00:41:42.950
is at.

00:41:42.950 --> 00:41:46.760
Partly, we'll be
doing some exercises

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:49.790
on this in the workshop.

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:52.460
In the first level, you see
the level of dehumanization

00:41:52.460 --> 00:41:55.730
is very low.

00:41:55.730 --> 00:41:59.600
You can communicate verbally
or through petitions

00:41:59.600 --> 00:42:02.390
or whatnot with your opponent.

00:42:02.390 --> 00:42:06.680
Tell your opponent we don't like
this, we want you to change it,

00:42:06.680 --> 00:42:10.280
and they can
conceivably respond.

00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:15.980
So the big question is,
yeah, but what if they don't?

00:42:15.980 --> 00:42:19.550
Well, that's when you have
to go into satyagraha.

00:42:19.550 --> 00:42:22.700
You have to resist
through nonviolent action.

00:42:22.700 --> 00:42:26.900
And the point of that, again,
to fall back on Gandhian

00:42:26.900 --> 00:42:29.870
terminology, is when you
really want something

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:33.560
important to be done, it's not
enough to appeal to the head.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:36.950
You have to be able to
move the heart also.

00:42:36.950 --> 00:42:39.350
And that is that
empathetic response

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:41.150
that we've been talking about.

00:42:41.150 --> 00:42:44.540
When you conquer and
convert your own anger,

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:49.610
it has a powerful effect
on everyone looking on.

00:42:49.610 --> 00:42:52.890
And what if you get to a place
where even that doesn't work,

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:56.180
and it's something that you
really, really care about?

00:42:56.180 --> 00:42:59.150
Well, you have an
ultimate weapon.

00:42:59.150 --> 00:43:02.060
Yes, I have used
that term advisedly.

00:43:02.060 --> 00:43:04.060
You have an ultimate
weapon in nonviolence,

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:06.090
and we hope you
don't have to use it.

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:09.380
But that weapon is if you are
willing to risk your life,

00:43:09.380 --> 00:43:12.950
it can have a tremendous impact.

00:43:12.950 --> 00:43:16.890
I don't like this idea
any more than you do.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:20.390
So what we try to
do is intervene more

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:24.540
at its lower level, at an
earlier stage of the conflict.

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:27.680
But it's critically important
to know what stage you're at.

00:43:27.680 --> 00:43:30.380
The classic example
that I like to use

00:43:30.380 --> 00:43:38.720
is, in 2003, they were getting
ready to wage war on Iraq.

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:42.930
12 million people, worldwide,
protested and said,

00:43:42.930 --> 00:43:44.480
we don't want this.

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:47.690
And the then-President
of the United States

00:43:47.690 --> 00:43:50.600
said, I don't have to pay
attention to those people.

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:53.390
They are just a focus group.

00:43:53.390 --> 00:43:56.480
Terms that you're
familiar with here.

00:43:56.480 --> 00:43:58.820
So what was he
saying, in our terms?

00:43:58.820 --> 00:44:02.990
He was saying, sorry,
people, we're in phase two,

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:04.800
not in phase one.

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:07.700
You're petitioning me
is not going to work.

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:11.030
You now have to go
into satyagraha.

00:44:11.030 --> 00:44:14.500
Even if we understood
that, which few of us did,

00:44:14.500 --> 00:44:15.990
we didn't know how to do it.

00:44:15.990 --> 00:44:19.690
We didn't have anything
really prepared.

00:44:19.690 --> 00:44:21.880
The famous episode where
Gandhi was getting off

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:24.730
a train and people come
at him with lathis.

00:44:24.730 --> 00:44:26.926
They want to beat him up.

00:44:26.926 --> 00:44:28.300
He said, you know,
it's not going

00:44:28.300 --> 00:44:29.950
to help you any to
break this head.

00:44:29.950 --> 00:44:32.590
And he's like, well,
we want thus and so.

00:44:32.590 --> 00:44:35.200
And what should we do then?

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.480
He said, well, you
must petition me

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:40.270
and then if I don't
respond to your petition,

00:44:40.270 --> 00:44:44.810
you must undertake a
hunger strike against me.

00:44:44.810 --> 00:44:46.990
And if I don't respond
to that hunger strike,

00:44:46.990 --> 00:44:49.070
you have to fast unto death.

00:44:49.070 --> 00:44:51.700
And they said, well, we're
not prepared to do that.

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:53.200
He said, well, then
you're not going

00:44:53.200 --> 00:44:55.240
to change my mind on this issue.

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:00.940
So in the first stage,
you can negotiate,

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:05.360
and the techniques of conflict
resolution are what you use.

00:45:05.360 --> 00:45:08.860
In the second phase, you
must go into satyagraha.

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:10.360
And in the third
phase, you must be

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:15.940
ready to make the
ultimate sacrifice.

00:45:15.940 --> 00:45:19.480
All along, you can also be
doing constructive program.

00:45:19.480 --> 00:45:20.920
Question.

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:23.436
AUDIENCE: So in
your Iraq example,

00:45:23.436 --> 00:45:25.810
it was too late to negotiate,
so resistance at that point

00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:28.942
would have been like the
soldiers just refused to go?

00:45:28.942 --> 00:45:31.150
MICHAEL NAGLER: If you were
a soldier, refusing to go

00:45:31.150 --> 00:45:34.780
would be very dramatic and a
correct and appropriate way

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:37.170
to do it, and some of them did.

00:45:37.170 --> 00:45:39.160
But if you are an
ordinary citizen,

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:43.180
you had other
methods open to you.

00:45:43.180 --> 00:45:46.780
I've had friends who got in
the way of troop trains, who

00:45:46.780 --> 00:45:48.530
blockaded army.

00:45:48.530 --> 00:45:50.740
There are many
people right now who

00:45:50.740 --> 00:45:53.080
are going to Creech
Air Force Base

00:45:53.080 --> 00:45:54.820
and protesting
against the drones.

00:45:54.820 --> 00:45:59.260
And not just holding up signs,
but blocking traffic in and out

00:45:59.260 --> 00:46:00.820
of the base.

00:46:00.820 --> 00:46:04.660
And there are a couple
of hundred techniques

00:46:04.660 --> 00:46:06.550
that are available to
us, if you went on.

00:46:06.550 --> 00:46:11.350
Now, all of them involve
risk-- the risk of arrest,

00:46:11.350 --> 00:46:13.150
for example.

00:46:13.150 --> 00:46:16.870
But if you care enough, on one
hand, that this thing really

00:46:16.870 --> 00:46:19.870
has to stop, I'm not
going to live with this,

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:22.360
and on the other
hand, you have faith

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:27.530
that nonviolence is a powerful
technique, that's what you do.

00:46:27.530 --> 00:46:28.750
And there have been some--

00:46:28.750 --> 00:46:31.330
the book that Nathan
was kind enough

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:34.540
to mention with a
little prompting,

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:36.640
"Search for a
Nonviolent Future,"

00:46:36.640 --> 00:46:42.010
we have maybe 60, 70 examples
of how satyagraha has worked.

00:46:42.010 --> 00:46:44.140
There's an eight-year
satyagraha that's

00:46:44.140 --> 00:46:48.070
been carried on in British
Columbia against an oil

00:46:48.070 --> 00:46:52.390
company that wanted to frack
their land, you know, come in.

00:46:52.390 --> 00:46:54.940
They had, like, 10
projects and they've now

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:58.150
had to give up seven of
them because they just made

00:46:58.150 --> 00:47:00.670
it too uncomfortable for
them, and showed them

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:06.352
how much they cared that they
did not want this to happen.

00:47:06.352 --> 00:47:08.560
And that's one of the big
changes that's taking place

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:10.350
in nonviolence, actually.

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:13.570
The way indigenous communities
have been becoming conscious

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:18.230
of their power in organizing.

00:47:18.230 --> 00:47:20.940
OK.

00:47:20.940 --> 00:47:23.790
So those are the three
conflict resolution techniques,

00:47:23.790 --> 00:47:27.120
satyagraha, and finally,
the ultimate sacrifice,

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:29.680
if you have to go that far.

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:31.470
Now, I wanted to
quickly share with you

00:47:31.470 --> 00:47:36.090
a scientific study that Frans
de Waal, who you heard from,

00:47:36.090 --> 00:47:37.500
carried on.

00:47:37.500 --> 00:47:40.830
They had this colony
of rhesus monkeys.

00:47:40.830 --> 00:47:42.930
Rhesus monkeys are
pretty bad hombres,

00:47:42.930 --> 00:47:45.900
as you can tell from this
picture, which of course, I've

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:48.889
chosen for the purpose.

00:47:48.889 --> 00:47:49.680
Here's another one.

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:53.060
I had to think of
this guy in New York.

00:47:53.060 --> 00:47:56.040
"You got some kind
of problem with dat?"

00:47:56.040 --> 00:47:58.740
So in this colony
of rhesus monkeys,

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:03.600
they introduced a
colony of stumptails.

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:04.800
Aren't they cute?

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:08.340
Now, stumptails are a little
bit bigger than rhesus monkeys,

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:12.510
but they're also much,
much less aggressive.

00:48:12.510 --> 00:48:15.600
So the experiment
was to see, how long

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:17.820
is it going to take
for the rhesus monkeys

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:22.050
to wipe up the cage with
these less aggressive guys?

00:48:22.050 --> 00:48:25.400
So a stumptail would
be sitting on a branch

00:48:25.400 --> 00:48:28.760
and a rhesus would come over
and say, get off of my branch.

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:31.320
And the stumptail
was saying, I refuse

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:33.600
to put up with your
injustice, but I'm open to you

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:35.260
as a primate.

00:48:35.260 --> 00:48:37.290
And sometimes,
they would actually

00:48:37.290 --> 00:48:39.520
offer a finger to be bitten.

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:41.580
The rhesus would bite
the finger, which hurts.

00:48:41.580 --> 00:48:43.815
I mean, these guys
are jaw muscles.

00:48:43.815 --> 00:48:49.560
[INAUDIBLE] But they
wouldn't back down.

00:48:49.560 --> 00:48:54.090
And to the astonishment
of the scientists,

00:48:54.090 --> 00:48:59.290
within a short period of
time, this stumptail culture,

00:48:59.290 --> 00:49:03.500
so to call it, had been
adopted by the rhesus monkeys.

00:49:03.500 --> 00:49:06.120
So here's these
animals, they never

00:49:06.120 --> 00:49:10.030
took my nonviolence
class, and yet

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:14.370
they could be reached by basic
nonviolent techniques, which

00:49:14.370 --> 00:49:16.800
required sacrifice and cost.

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:20.610
But their little primate
brains were changed.

00:49:20.610 --> 00:49:23.610
And so that was the
second big surprise.

00:49:23.610 --> 00:49:26.310
The nonviolent
resistance was working.

00:49:26.310 --> 00:49:29.250
The amazing thing was that
the rhesus adopted it.

00:49:29.250 --> 00:49:30.690
And now comes the third.

00:49:30.690 --> 00:49:33.090
Third is the winner, right?

00:49:33.090 --> 00:49:36.810
So they took the stumptails
out after a while

00:49:36.810 --> 00:49:39.900
and watched to see, how long is
it going to take for the rhesus

00:49:39.900 --> 00:49:44.310
to go back to their bad
old, New York subway ways?

00:49:44.310 --> 00:49:46.110
And guess what?

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:48.100
They still haven't done that.

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:52.980
So the conversion to
nonviolence is a robust change.

00:49:52.980 --> 00:49:55.260
I wanted to introduce
you to these two guys

00:49:55.260 --> 00:50:00.450
because you're going to be using
their story in the workshop.

00:50:00.450 --> 00:50:03.170
These two gentlemen were part
of this new institution called

00:50:03.170 --> 00:50:07.450
Unarmed Civilian Peacekeeping
or Unarmed Civilian Protection.

00:50:07.450 --> 00:50:10.410
They were in a UN IDP camp--

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:13.080
Internally Displaced
Person camp--

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:17.580
in South Sudan, one of the most
violent places in the world

00:50:17.580 --> 00:50:18.720
right now.

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:21.930
And suddenly, that camp
was attacked by a militia.

00:50:21.930 --> 00:50:23.790
These two guys ran
into a little hut

00:50:23.790 --> 00:50:26.670
to protect, to save themselves.

00:50:26.670 --> 00:50:30.660
They found 13 women and
children in that hut.

00:50:30.660 --> 00:50:34.020
And a couple of minutes
later, the militia burst in--

00:50:34.020 --> 00:50:37.800
AK-47s, axes, sharpened sticks.

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:42.060
And they saw these two, who
were obviously not Sudanese,

00:50:42.060 --> 00:50:44.604
and said to them,
hey, you get out.

00:50:44.604 --> 00:50:46.020
Now, you know
exactly what's going

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:48.240
to happen when they get out.

00:50:48.240 --> 00:50:52.320
Outside the hut, they're
listening to gunfire.

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:56.050
But these two showed
their badges and said,

00:50:56.050 --> 00:50:59.770
I'm sorry we're international
protection officers

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:01.500
and we're not leaving.

00:51:01.500 --> 00:51:04.110
So there's this flipping
the script, right--

00:51:04.110 --> 00:51:06.690
intense moment of
confrontation--

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:09.930
and the militia turned
around and left.

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:13.290
Not only that, but in the 20
minutes that this raid went on,

00:51:13.290 --> 00:51:15.390
this happened three times.

00:51:15.390 --> 00:51:17.340
Militia came in
and said, you know,

00:51:17.340 --> 00:51:19.048
we're going to kill
you, get out of here,

00:51:19.048 --> 00:51:20.670
threatened them with weapons.

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:26.280
And these two refused to back
down, and the militia left.

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:30.150
Outside that little
hut, 60 people

00:51:30.150 --> 00:51:33.210
were massacred in 20 minutes.

00:51:33.210 --> 00:51:35.570
Inside the hut, nobody was hurt.

00:51:35.570 --> 00:51:37.980
There's a very
dramatic illustration

00:51:37.980 --> 00:51:41.169
of the power of nonviolence.

00:51:41.169 --> 00:51:42.210
So that's the background.

00:51:42.210 --> 00:51:44.130
We may be using
this story later.

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:46.300
So what can we do about it?

00:51:46.300 --> 00:51:50.070
I'm just going to have to
go over this very quickly.

00:51:50.070 --> 00:51:51.990
We have a scheme
called Roadmap, which

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:54.650
divides up the
problem into three

00:51:54.650 --> 00:51:57.690
and guides you from
personal empowerment,

00:51:57.690 --> 00:52:01.770
take us through a constructive
program, to resistance.

00:52:01.770 --> 00:52:05.310
You can find this and
much supportive material

00:52:05.310 --> 00:52:06.480
on our website.

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:08.670
But what I wanted
to share with you--

00:52:08.670 --> 00:52:13.410
and if this works, by the
way, this next move of mine,

00:52:13.410 --> 00:52:16.920
it's going to be the greatest
technological triumph

00:52:16.920 --> 00:52:18.060
of this slideshow.

00:52:18.060 --> 00:52:19.350
So wish me luck.

00:52:19.350 --> 00:52:22.230
Here we go.

00:52:22.230 --> 00:52:24.690
Cha.

00:52:24.690 --> 00:52:27.480
Thank you, Marie.

00:52:27.480 --> 00:52:31.480
So this is the inner circle,
which we've just enlarged.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:34.770
And we have these
five suggestions.

00:52:34.770 --> 00:52:37.020
You want to be very
careful about your exposure

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:39.750
to violence in the mass media.

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:44.610
I'm really particularly glad to
be sharing, with you, this idea

00:52:44.610 --> 00:52:47.700
because I think here you can
have some influence over how

00:52:47.700 --> 00:52:50.850
the mass media works.

00:52:50.850 --> 00:52:53.880
Learn everything you
can about nonviolence.

00:52:53.880 --> 00:52:55.980
You'll never guess
where I will direct you

00:52:55.980 --> 00:52:57.570
if you want to do more of that.

00:52:57.570 --> 00:52:59.970
Mettacenter.org.

00:52:59.970 --> 00:53:01.380
Take up a spiritual practice.

00:53:01.380 --> 00:53:04.110
I know Meng isn't
here anymore, but we

00:53:04.110 --> 00:53:07.680
do have mindfulness
that's going on here.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:10.370
We recommend one called
passage meditation.

00:53:10.370 --> 00:53:13.200
It's what most of us
do at the Metta Center.

00:53:13.200 --> 00:53:14.890
And the website
there is bmcm.org.

00:53:17.690 --> 00:53:21.331
Stands for Blue Mountain
Center of Meditation dot org.

00:53:21.331 --> 00:53:24.420
Re-personalization, just
be more personal with all

00:53:24.420 --> 00:53:25.620
your human interactions.

00:53:25.620 --> 00:53:29.280
And finally, it's
quite helpful if you

00:53:29.280 --> 00:53:32.820
learn the basic outlines
of the New Story

00:53:32.820 --> 00:53:35.610
and be ready to share
it on any occasion

00:53:35.610 --> 00:53:38.220
because that's how
paradigms change.

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:38.827
Nandu?

00:53:38.827 --> 00:53:40.035
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I just want--

00:53:40.035 --> 00:53:43.357
AUDIENCE: They use violence
and somehow nobody gets hurt.

00:53:43.357 --> 00:53:44.440
MICHAEL NAGLER: Oh, right.

00:53:44.440 --> 00:53:44.939
Right.

00:53:44.939 --> 00:53:45.470
Yes.

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:49.640
That's one of the real delusions
about-- thank you, Nandu--

00:53:49.640 --> 00:53:53.510
one of the real delusions
about the Old Story

00:53:53.510 --> 00:53:56.670
is that it's safe
to use violence.

00:53:56.670 --> 00:54:00.110
And so you have Superman--
and this is very embarrassing

00:54:00.110 --> 00:54:04.520
because I actually wrote
some of the scripts

00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:07.880
for some "Superboy" comics
when I was very, very young.

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:10.212
I just plain didn't
know any better.

00:54:10.212 --> 00:54:11.420
I was growing up in Brooklyn.

00:54:11.420 --> 00:54:13.220
Anyway, never mind.

00:54:13.220 --> 00:54:16.490
The idea is if you
use nonviolence,

00:54:16.490 --> 00:54:20.450
people are immediately
overcome, the problem is solved,

00:54:20.450 --> 00:54:22.270
and you don't get hurt.

00:54:22.270 --> 00:54:25.910
Whereas the reality is that
if you incarcerate people,

00:54:25.910 --> 00:54:29.240
they will recommit crimes
when they get out of prison

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:34.070
at a rate of 76% nationwide.

00:54:34.070 --> 00:54:38.340
In restorative justice, the
rate will be more like 2% or 3%.

00:54:38.340 --> 00:54:39.020
Thank you.

00:54:39.020 --> 00:54:40.070
Thank you very much.

